(1)
17th Street at N.W. corner of Ninth Avenue and west on north side. The frame houses were built not later than 1879, as was also Engine House No. 3, 417 West 17th Street, the three-story brick building in left centre. The latter is the oldest brick building in the block.

April 30, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)
No's 409 to 419, just west of Ninth Avenue. The three story building shown in the foreground (417) is Engine House No. 3.

June 11, 1935.

P. L. Sperr.

(3)
No's 415 to 423; slightly westward. Clearance shown on the extreme right is at No's. 425 & 427.

113 and 115 Ninth Avenue, at and adjoining the N.W. corner of W. 17th Street (foreground), showing the rears of these frame buildings as viewed across the cleared site where stood No's 405-7-9 W. 17th Street. These were also
of frame construction.
The new law tenement at the left is No. 117 Ninth Avenue. Tho margin on the right eliminates a view of that thorough fare
and its elevated line.
April 15, 1936

Ninth Avenue (elevated line thereon), south from W. 17th (left) Street. Below same and occupying an entire square block is the mammoth Port of N.Y. Authority Building. View No. 3 shows the westerly portion of same on the eastern side of the Avenue between 16th and 15th Streets.

No. 2 is an eastward view on 17th Street, showing structures at the S.E. and N.E. corners. To the left of the latter is a vacant lot which has recently been cleared. Upon this site will be erected a new 6 story apartment according to the New York Times of May 9, 1938. This is the S.E. corner of W. 18th Street.

June 15, 1938.
Views 1,2 and 3

P. L. Sperr
